body:
@leventov 
> Side note: enable caching (druid supports both historical- and broker-level query results cache) to reduce the amount of repetitive calculations.

Indeed, query caching can reduce the amount of repetitive calculations. It stores the results on a per segment basis and **a given query**. This proposal pre-calculates the results based on dimensions and the results are considered as a datasource. We can calculate **any query** (with given dimensions) based on the datasource instead of **a given query.**

@zhangxinyu1 thanks for the proposal. I wonder what are the primary benefits of the derivedDataSource. Is the query speed the only one?

> It's a good question! I hope the query can be query can be served partially by derived datasource and partially by original. However, in this implementation, it's only served fully by original. Therefore, in this implementation, it cannot support realtime ingestion.

This can also happen even in batch append ingestion. I think this is important and should be supported because most Druid users will append new data to existing dataSources in some ways.

@donpinkus `"TopNs can be made more accurate by increasing the threshold."` comment in the document refers to increasing the the number `druid.query.topN.minTopNThreshold` (1000 by default) explained later in the doc. if that is true then document is misleading and needs to be corrected.

I don't think that increasing `threshold` param in the query would increase accuracy.

other devs can probably comment if there is something I'm missing.

@kaytrance can you try to use the same "metricSpec" as is used by original ingestion spec and see if that produces sensible metrics.

reindexing code is expected to work with exact same metricSpec that is used for original ingestion to support the "delta ingestion" use case.

we'll update the docs if that fixes the issue for you and indeed the cause here.

@nishantmonu51 "dimensions" isn't just a list of strings but list of `DimensionSpec` which provide additional functionality like extraction functions, lookups etc. So, in general, user should be able to provide it explicitly and not redundant.
but, yes, it could be made optional where "dimensions" is generated from given subtotals specially if their query looked like the one in example description. I don't see much value in that considering the type of queries I see. It would be a minor and independent change that could be done later as well.

I called it "subtotalsSpec" based on the term used in oracle https://docs.oracle.com/cd/B28359_01/server.111/b28314/tdpdw_sql.htm#TDPDW00711 and that most users were familiar with, but I wouldn't mind changing the name if other proposed options make more sense.

@hamlet-lee  in my testing, straight forward `fs.getClass().getMethod(..)` does not appear to work because `rename` method is not PUBLIC. This is noted in the [javadocs](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html#getMethod-java.lang.String-java.lang.Class...- ) too
. So, I had to add a recursive impl to go over all superclasses to find the `rename` method. See `findRenameMethodRecursively(..)` added in `HadoopFsWrapper.java` .

I wonder how it is working for you without this recursive search. Have you done anything else special in your setup?
